## 2. SCSS class naming

### Root class

Every component gets exactly one root CSS class. Derive it from the component name using the **full** prefix name (no abbreviations — readability costs nothing; minification handles production):

| Component prefix | CSS prefix |
|-----------------|------------|
| `Page_` | `page__` |
| `Manager_` | `manager__` |
| `Editor_` | `editor__` |
| `Renderer_` | `renderer__` |
| `Panel_` | `panel__` |
| `Component_` | `component__` |
| `Header_` | `header__` |
| `Dialog_` | `dialog__` |

Append the domain in kebab-case:

```
Manager_Article           →  .manager__article
Editor_Article            →  .editor__article
Panel_ArticleList         →  .panel__article-list
Renderer_ArticleEditor    →  .renderer__article-editor
```

**The root is always a class selector, never an ID.** IDs are reserved for mouse-interactivity pop-up anchors registered with `openContent`.

### Sub-element naming

Use the root class as the SCSS nesting root. Sub-elements extend the root name with `__element`. Let SCSS nesting handle depth — never flatten long chains.

```scss
// Correct
.manager__article {
  .manager__article__selector {
    .manager__article__selector-header { }
    .manager__article__selector-title { }
  }
}

// Wrong — flat deep chain
.manager__article__selector__header__title__icon { }
```

### Modifiers

Use single modifier classes (`.selected`, `.edit-mode`, `.disabled`, `.active`, `.error`). Double-dash BEM modifiers are banned — SCSS nesting already provides the context they pretend to add.

```scss
.manager__article__list-item {
  &.selected  { background: tokens.$surface-selected; }
  &.edit-mode { border-color: transparent; }
}
```

