## 4. Design application — parent scopes children

Thunderstorm library components (`TS_DropDown`, `TS_Input`, `TS_Textarea`, `TS_Tabs`, `TS_Checkbox`, `TS_PropRenderer`) render minimal structure with no default visual design. **The Page or Manager that owns the visual context is responsible for applying design to its descendant library components.**

Do this by extending your app's design placeholders within the Page/Manager SCSS root scope:

```scss
// Manager_Article.scss
.manager__article {
  .ts-prop-renderer { @extend %AppDesign_PropRenderer; }
  .ts-dropdown      { @extend %AppDesign_DropDown; }
  .ts-input         { @extend %AppDesign_Input; }
  .ts-textarea      { @extend %AppDesign_TextArea; }
}
```

Your app defines these design placeholders once in a shared SCSS module (e.g. `@your-app/styles/design`). Import with `@use '@your-app/styles/design' as *;`.

**Never** apply design tokens at the individual Renderer or Field level — those components have no knowledge of which design context they are in. If a sub-component needs a visual tweak specific to one parent context, the parent's SCSS scopes it.

### consts.scss — shared placeholders within a component family

When a group of sibling components (e.g. all tab content components inside one Editor) share a layout pattern, define it once as a SCSS placeholder in a `consts.scss` co-located with the parent:

```scss
// Editor_Article/consts.scss
%ArticleEditor_TabLayout {
  padding: 24px 0;
  & > .ts-grid {
    column-gap: 48px;
    row-gap: 12px;
    grid-template-columns: max-content 1fr;
  }
}
```

Sibling SCSS files extend it:

```scss
// Editor_Article_General.scss
.editor__article__general {
  @extend %ArticleEditor_TabLayout;
}
```

