## 7. React component structure

### Standard class layout

```tsx
export class Editor_Article extends ComponentSync<Props, State>
  implements DispatcherInterface<DispatcherType_Article> {

  protected deriveStateFromProps(nextProps: Props, state: State) { ... }

  private onSave = async () => { ... };

  render() {
    return <LL_V_L className={'editor__article'}>{...}</LL_V_L>;
  }

  private renderHeader = () => { ... };
  private renderForm   = () => { ... };
}
```

**Never add section-separator comments** (e.g. `// ######################## Lifecycle ########################`). They are noise — method names and class structure already communicate intent. If a class is so large that you need landmarks to navigate it, that is a signal to decompose into smaller components, not to add banners.

### Choosing the component base class

| Base class | When to use |
|------------|-------------|
| Function component | Default for flat rendering — receives props, returns JSX, no internal state. |
| `React.Component` | Needs internal state (`setState`) but no complex prop-to-state derivation or Thunderstorm dispatcher integration. |
| `ComponentSync` | Needs complex state management (`deriveStateFromProps`, `reDeriveState`) or Thunderstorm dispatcher integration (implements `DispatcherInterface`). |

Pick the simplest base that satisfies the component's requirements. Do not use `ComponentSync` when a function component or plain `React.Component` suffices — unnecessary framework coupling adds cognitive weight. Do not use `React.Component` when a function component with no state would do.

### Props and State

Always define `Props` and `State` as top-level local types. Never use inline object types in the class signature.

```tsx
type Props = {
  entityId: UniqueId;
  editMode: boolean;
};

type State = {
  editable: EditableDBItemV3<DBProto_SomeEntity>;
};
```

### deriveStateFromProps

Map props to state here. Do not use `componentDidMount` + `setState` for initialisation.

```tsx
protected deriveStateFromProps(nextProps: Props, state: State) {
  if (state.editable?.item._id !== nextProps.entityId)
    state.editable = this.buildEditable(nextProps.entityId);
  return state;
}
```

