## 9. Edit/view mode

### Structurally different modes — use Component_SwitchView

When view and edit have different layouts (different components entirely):

```tsx
private renderEntityEditor(editable: EditableItem<UI_SomeEntity>) {
  return <Component_SwitchView
    mode={this.state.editMode ? 'edit' : 'view'}
    modes={[
      {
        key: 'view',
        renderer: () => <Renderer_EntityDetails editable={editable} toggleEdit={this.toggleEdit} />
      },
      {
        key: 'edit',
        permissionKey: this.permissionKey_Edit,
        renderer: () => <Renderer_EntityEditor editable={editable} toggleMode={this.toggleEdit} />
      }
    ]}
  />;
}
```

### Structurally same modes — use disabled prop

When the layout is identical in both modes and only field interactivity changes, pass `editMode` down and use `disabled`:

```tsx
<TS_Input
  value={editable.item.label}
  onChange={this.onLabelChange}
  disabled={!props.editMode}
/>
```

Your app's design system should define the `disabled` visual on inputs (typically: transparent border, plain text cursor, no background). Do not add custom disabled overrides per component — handle it once in the design placeholder.

